## Multiview Source-Available Non-Commercial License

Licensor: Aperim Pty Ltd (ABN 46 150 699 737) ("we", "us", "our").
Software: the Multiview software and any files distributed with this License ("the
software").

### 0. Purpose and intent (recital)

We make the source of the software available and grant free use for genuine
personal, home, hobby, and non-commercial purposes, together with three specific
free exceptions defined below. All other use is commercial use and requires a
separate Commercial License from us. We deliberately treat use by businesses,
educational institutions, governments, product/appliance makers, and content
creators/streamers as commercial use. This is a departure from some licenses that
call themselves "non-commercial"; any industry custom that would treat educational
or governmental use as free does not apply to this License.

### 1. Acceptance

In order to receive this License, you must agree to its rules. Those rules are both
obligations under this License and conditions to your license. You must not do
anything with the software that triggers a rule you cannot or will not follow.

### 2. Grant of free use

We grant you a copyright license to use, copy, modify, and distribute the software,
for free, but only for a Permitted Purpose (Section 3) and subject to the rules and
notices below. This License does not grant rights in any third-party material except
as that material's own license allows (Section 9).

### 3. Permitted Purpose (free use)

A Permitted Purpose is only one of the following:

3.1 Personal / home use. Use unconnected with any trade, business, or profession of
the user — that is, for private study, private entertainment, hobby projects,
amateur pursuits, experiment, and testing — by a natural person acting in a personal
capacity, without any anticipated commercial application. Eligibility under this
clause turns on the capacity in which the software is used, not on the user's status:
a person who is a sole trader, business owner, employee, teacher, public servant, or
content creator may still use the software under this clause for genuinely personal
use unconnected with their trade, business, profession, or institution. The same
person's use in or for their trade, business, profession, institution, government
role, or content production is Commercial Use (Section 4), not personal use.

3.2 First Nations Owned Broadcaster Exception (Section 5.1).

3.3 Community Broadcaster Exception (Section 5.2).

3.4 Content Creator Exception (Section 5.3).

Any use that is not a Permitted Purpose is Commercial Use and requires a Commercial
License (Section 6).

### 4. Commercial Use (requires a paid Commercial License)

"Commercial Use" means any use of the software other than a Permitted Purpose.

The trigger is use. It is irrelevant whether you have modified the software, whether
you obtained it directly from us or from a fork, mirror, redistribution, or any other
third party, and whether or not you further distribute it. Running or otherwise using
the software — as supplied by us or as modified, and whether standalone or
incorporated into anything else — for any purpose that is not a Permitted Purpose is
Commercial Use and requires a Commercial License. Building a product, service, fork,
or derivative on the software does not escape this License: a fork or derivative is
licensed to its recipients only on these same terms, and any commercial use of it (or
of the unmodified software) is Commercial Use.

For the avoidance of doubt and without limitation, Commercial Use includes:

(a) any use in or for the trade, business, or profession of any business, company,
partnership, sole trader, or other for-profit entity (including internal use), or by
a person acting in the course of such a trade, business, or profession. For clarity,
the genuinely personal, non-trade use of a natural person who happens to be a sole
trader or business owner is governed by Section 3.1, not this paragraph;

(b) any use by or for, or in connection with the activities of, an educational
institution — including a school, college, university, or training organisation — or
by its staff or students acting in that capacity (a person who is a teacher or
student may still use the software for genuinely personal, non-institutional purposes
under Section 3.1);

(c) any use by or for, or in connection with the activities of, a government,
government agency, statutory authority, or public body at any level (local, state or
territory, national, or supranational), or by an officer or employee acting in that
capacity;

(d) incorporating, bundling, embedding, or distributing the software (modified or
not) in or as a product, appliance, hardware unit, image, container, or service
supplied or offered to any third party, whether or not for charge ("productization");

(e) use by a streamer, content creator, influencer, journalist, or media producer to
create, produce, or distribute content, except as permitted by the Content Creator
Exception (5.3);

(f) any use directly or indirectly intended for or directed towards commercial
advantage, revenue, sponsorship, audience-building for gain, or monetary
compensation.

A user's status as a non-profit, charity, or not-for-profit does not by itself make a
use a Permitted Purpose.

### 5. The three free exceptions

Each exception applies only to the exempt entity's own activities. It does not permit
any non-exempt third party (including an integrator, contractor, agent, or commercial
service provider) to operate the software as, or as part of, a commercial product or
service by relying on the exception (the "no-conduit rule"). Where two or more
entities or Channels are under common ownership or control, or operate as a single
brand or undertaking in substance, they are treated as one user for the purposes of
every threshold in this Section (the "aggregation rule"). Eligibility is assessed by
substance, not labels.

5.1 First Nations Owned Broadcaster Exception. Free use is permitted by a First
Nations Owned Broadcaster, meaning an entity that produces or distributes broadcast
or streamed media content and satisfies either limb:

(A) Registry limb — in Australia, it is registered under the Corporations (Aboriginal
and Torres Strait Islander) Act 2006 (Cth) with the Office of the Registrar of
Indigenous Corporations; or holds an Australian community broadcasting licence
allocated to represent an Aboriginal and/or Torres Strait Islander community interest;
or is a member of First Nations Media Australia; or, outside Australia, is recognised
as an Indigenous broadcaster by the relevant national Indigenous broadcasting body or
regulator (including, without limitation, an iwi radio station or Whakaata Māori in
Aotearoa New Zealand, an Indigenous broadcaster recognised by the CRTC in Canada, or
a Tribal radio licensee recognised by the U.S. FCC); or

(B) Ownership-and-control limb — more than fifty percent (50%) of both (i) the
beneficial ownership of the entity and (ii) the persons who control its financial and
operational decisions are First Nations persons (being Aboriginal and/or Torres
Strait Islander persons in Australia, Māori in Aotearoa New Zealand, or Indigenous,
Aboriginal, First Nations, Métis, Inuit, or Native peoples recognised in the relevant
country), and the entity is not Controlled in Substance, directly or indirectly, by
any person who is not a First Nations person or First Nations entity. "Controlled in
Substance" means having the practical ability to direct or veto the entity's
financial or operational decisions, whether through shareholding, board composition,
financing arrangements, intellectual-property licensing, contractual veto or approval
rights, or any similar means, regardless of formal ownership percentages.

5.2 Community Broadcaster Exception. Free use is permitted by a Community
Broadcaster, meaning an entity that (a) holds a community broadcasting licence (or an
equivalent community or non-profit broadcasting licence class issued by a national
broadcasting regulator), is operated on a not-for-profit basis, and is not controlled
by a government or political party; and (b) whose total Sponsorship Revenue in its
most recently completed financial year did not exceed USD $1,000,000.

"Sponsorship Revenue" means the gross aggregate amount received or receivable, in
money or money's worth, by the entity and its related and commonly-controlled
entities in that financial year as consideration for broadcasting, streaming, or
publishing sponsorship announcements, acknowledgements of financial support, or
equivalent paid acknowledgements (in Australia, "sponsorship" within the meaning of
the Broadcasting Services Act 1992 (Cth) and the ACMA Community Broadcasting
Sponsorship Guidelines), before deduction of any costs, agency fees, or commissions.
It excludes genuine grants, donations, and membership subscriptions that are not
consideration for a sponsorship announcement. Amounts in a substance equivalent to
sponsorship are counted even if labelled otherwise (e.g. "underwriting" or
"partnership fees").

5.3 Content Creator Exception. Free use is permitted by a natural person, or a group
of natural persons acting together, who uses the software to produce or distribute
their own content and whose total Audience Count is fewer than 55,000.

"Channel" means any account, page, feed, profile, show, list, or comparable presence
operated by the user (or under their control or in their name) on any platform
through which content is distributed to an audience (video, audio, streaming, social,
messaging, podcast, newsletter).

"Audience Count" means the simple arithmetic sum, across all of the user's Channels,
of the largest applicable audience figure natively reported by each platform for that
Channel (subscribers, followers, members, paid subscribers, or mailing-list
subscribers; for podcasts, the average unique downloads per episode over the trailing
90 days). The user is not required or permitted to de-duplicate the same person across
Channels; the figure is the plain sum of per-Channel counts.

Channels operated by an entity the user controls, where the content is the user's,
are included. Where two or more nominally separate creators or Channels are under
common ownership or control, or operate as a single brand or undertaking in substance,
their Audience Counts are aggregated under the Section 5 aggregation rule.

