### 7. Self-certification, audit, currency, and growing out of an exception

7.1 Self-certification. Eligibility for a Permitted Purpose or exception is based on
your good-faith self-certification of the relevant facts, assessed at first use and
on the first day of each calendar quarter. We may, on at least 14 days' written notice
and no more than once in any 12-month period, ask you for reasonable evidence that you
meet a claimed exception (e.g. registry records, the relevant revenue line, or native
platform audience dashboards). If you cannot or do not substantiate eligibility within
the notice period, or you have materially misrepresented eligibility, you are treated
as having made Commercial Use without a license from the date the misrepresentation
began, and you must obtain a Commercial License (and may owe back-fees).

7.2 Currency conversion. Where an amount is in a currency other than US dollars, it is
converted to US dollars at the exchange rate published by the Reserve Bank of
Australia (or, where the entity is outside Australia, the principal central bank of
the entity's home country) on the last day of the relevant financial year (or the most
recent prior published rate).

7.3 Growing out of an exception (transition). If you qualified for an exception and
later cease to qualify (by exceeding a threshold, losing not-for-profit status, or
otherwise), you may continue to use the version(s) of the software you were already
using under that exception for a transition period of 90 days after the first
quarterly assessment date on which you cease to qualify. After that, continued use —
and any upgrade, new version, or new installation — requires a Commercial License.
Later falling back below a threshold does not retroactively restore the exception.

